image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umustelafuro.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mustela Furo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/1/01 6:46:38 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> A little gnome's take on things...</span><hr size=1> Well, I figured after reading both threads on this subject, I figured I'd throw my own views on abortion into the mix.  (Forgive me if they're a little off topic.  I'm just stating my opinions.)<br>
<br>
When I was in high school, I was about as anti-abortion as you could get.  I mean, I was <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>bad</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  I thought of the girls who were pro-choice as sluts.  I mean, obviously, if they're pro-choice, they must be sleeping around and may end up getting pregnant; that's why they want the choice, right?  (I told ya I was bad.)<br>
<br>
I stayed this way all throughout high school, until about the tail end of my senior year.  I actually started thinking about what would happen once I became sexually active, about what would happen if I <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>did</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> end up getting pregnant before I was ready.  And you know what?  My views changed.  I prayed that it would never happen (ya know... getting pregnant), but thought to myself, &quot;I'd <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>really</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> like to have that choice available to me if something <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>did</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> happen that I wasn't prepared for.&quot;<br>
<br>
Even now, though, I don't consider myself to be pro-abortion.  That is to say, if I were to get pregnant and didn't want the baby (which I'm quite sure I wouldn't), I would try to consider adoption as the first choice.  However, if, for whatever reason, that wasn't feasible, I would like to have another choice open that would allow me to not have to care for this child.  That may not make sense to some people, but it's the way I've felt about it for quite some time.<br>
<br>
The only thing that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>really</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> irks me about abortion is the people who abuse it.  Basically, the people who keep fucking and fucking and fucking, without ever using any form of contraception.  If they're paying for the abortions with their own money, then fine, I don't care.  However, if welfare (or whatever government allotment; translation: my tax dollars) is paying for each and every abortion, I say cut it.  Literally.  Tie the woman's fucking tubes, or make her pay for her own abortion.  If she chooses to have the baby instead, cut her off from receiving welfare for the child, since the government has already paid for enough of her mistakes.  (I also feel the same way about women who keep having children while they're on welfare.  Give them two choices:  tubal ligation, or no more welfare.)  <br>
<br>
But, aside from previous paragraph's gripe, I do feel that women should have the choice, just so long as it's educated.  You know, if they check into Planned Parenthood or a similar establishment to see what choices they should make, I would hope that they receive pamphlets in regards to <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>every</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> option (keeping the baby, adoption, abortion, etc.), and not just abortion (which I have heard Planned Parenthood has been rumored to do).<br>
<br>
